```java
import java.util.*;

public class Task173 {
    public static String longestDupSubstring(String s) {
        if (s == null || s.length() < 2 || s.length() > 30000) {
            return "";
        }
        
        int n = s.length();
        
        // Check from longest possible length to shortest
        for (int len = n - 1; len >= 1; len--) {
            Set<String> seen = new HashSet<>();
            
            for (int i = 0; i <= n - len; i++) {
                String sub = s.substring(i, i + len);
                if (seen.contains(sub)) {
                    return sub;
                }
                seen.add(sub);
            }
        }
        
        return "";
    }
    
    I'll systematically check substrings, starting from the longest possible length. By iterating from longest to shortest, I ensure I'll find the longest duplicated substring first. The hash set allows quick duplicate detection, making the approach efficient for moderate-length strings.

    The method handles edge cases like short strings or strings with no duplicates by returning an empty string. It's a straightforward, readable solution that prioritizes clarity over extreme optimization.
}
```

